    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:735a3581-8e9d-4849-a193-99eaa6aab3f3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 35-year-old male who presents to the gastroenterology outpatient clinic with a several-month history of persistent heartburn, acid regurgitation, and a sour taste in his mouth, particularly after meals and when lying down at night. He describes a burning sensation rising from his chest toward his throat, often accompanied by a dull precordial chest pain that he initially feared was cardiac in origin. These symptoms frequently wake him in the early hours of the morning. He also complains of occasional bloating and an uncomfortable feeling of fullness after eating, along with a mild chronic cough that he initially attributed to seasonal allergies.\n\n{patientName} works as a software developer, spending the majority of his workday seated at a desk for 9–10 hours. His lifestyle is largely sedentary, with little time for regular exercise. He carries a BMI of 27.4 and has a well-established habit of eating large, late-evening meals — often within an hour of going to bed. He is an enthusiastic home brewer and craft beer hobbyist, regularly tasting and consuming carbonated alcoholic beverages on weekends; he also enjoys hosting dinner parties where rich, fatty, and spicy cuisines are a staple. He frequently consumes spicy and fatty foods, drinks two to three cups of coffee daily, and enjoys a glass or two of red wine on weekends alongside his craft beers. He is a non-smoker.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys video gaming late into the night — often reclining on the sofa with snacks after a large evening meal — reading science fiction novels, and occasional weekend hikes with friends. The post-meal reclining during long gaming sessions is a recognised personal trigger for his reflux episodes. He is socially active and lives with his long-term partner in a city apartment. He reports moderate levels of work-related stress, especially during project deadlines, which he notices tends to worsen his gastrointestinal symptoms.\n\n{patientName} appears well-nourished and mildly overweight on examination. He is in no acute distress. His abdomen is soft with mild epigastric tenderness on deep palpation. No guarding or rebound tenderness is noted. Bowel sounds are normal. He has a confirmed small sliding hiatal hernia on endoscopy, which predisposes him to reflux by impairing the normal anti-reflux barrier at the gastro-oesophageal junction."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
